  "body": {
    "view": {
      "representation": "view",
      "value": "<p><style>[data-colorid=olp1rcyor0]{color:#3d90b3} html[data-color-mode=dark] [data-colorid=olp1rcyor0]{color:#4c9fc2}[data-colorid=r2nahotx4l]{color:#3d90b3} html[data-color-mode=dark] [data-colorid=r2nahotx4l]{color:#4c9fc2}[data-colorid=r3sxpqjgkf]{color:#3d90b3} html[data-color-mode=dark] [data-colorid=r3sxpqjgkf]{color:#4c9fc2}</style><span class=\"legacy-color-text-default\"><br /><br />This node allows two Lama materials to be mixed together. It works like a classic &quot;over&quot; operator in compositing.</span></p><p><span class=\"legacy-color-text-default\">The Mix parameter can be driven by a texture. <br />The black areas will show material1 and the white ones material2. <br />Any gray values will mix between the two and will be more expensive to compute.</span></p><p><span data-colorid=\"olp1rcyor0\">Material 1</span></p><p><span class=\"legacy-color-text-default\">This is the first material to mix</span></p><p><span data-colorid=\"r2nahotx4l\">Material 2</span></p><p><span class=\"legacy-color-text-default\">The second material to be mixed.</span></p><p><span data-colorid=\"r3sxpqjgkf\">Mix</span></p><p><span class=\"legacy-color-text-default\">The mix value defines the balance between the two materials, ranging from 0 (Material 1 only) to 1 (Material 2 only).&nbsp;</span></p><p><span class=\"legacy-color-text-default\">It can also be used as a &quot;Material 2 over Material 1&quot; mask.</span></p><p><br /></p>"
    }
  },
